# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dearpygui
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] GPUs are also increasingly being used for artificial intelligence (AI) processing due to linear algebra acceleration, which is also used extensively in graphics processing.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] This contrasts with earlier graphics controllers known as video display controllers which had no internal calculation capabilities, or blitters, which performed only basic memory movement operations.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] The modern GPU emerged during the 1990s, adding the ability to perform operations like drawing lines and text without CPU help, and later adding 3D functionality.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Graphics functions are generally independent and this lends these tasks to being implemented on separate calculation engines.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Modern GPUs include hundreds, or thousands, of calculation units.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] This made them useful for non-graphic calculations involving embarrassingly parallel problems due to their parallel structure.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] The ability of GPUs to rapidly perform vast numbers of calculations has led to their adoption in diverse fields including artificial intelligence (AI) where they excel at handling data-intensive and computationally demanding tasks.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Other non-graphical uses include the training of neural networks and cryptocurrency mining.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Many companies have produced GPUs under a number of brand names.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] In 2009, Intel, Nvidia, and AMD/ATI were the market share leaders, with 49.4%, 27.8%, and 20.6% market share respectively.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] In addition, Matrox while originally producing custom solutions, now customizes GPUs from Intel and AMD for workstation usage.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Chinese companies such as Jingjia Micro have also produced GPUs for the domestic market although in terms of worldwide sales, they lag behind market leaders.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Several factors of GPU construction affect the performance of the card for real-time rendering, such as the size of the connector pathways in the semiconductor device fabrication, the clock signal frequency, and the number and size of various on-chip memory caches.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] GPU performance is typically measured in floating point operations per second (FLOPS); Modern GPUs typically deliver performance measured in teraflops (TFLOPS).
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] This is an estimated performance measure, and should not be treated as fact, as other factors can affect actual performance.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Modern GPUs also include dedicated hardware blocks for ray tracing, video encoding, and AI acceleration.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] In personal computers, there are two main forms of GPUs: dedicated graphics (also called discrete graphics) and integrated graphics (also called shared graphics solutions, integrated graphics processors (IGP), or unified memory architecture (UMA).
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Technologies such as Scalable Link Interface (SLI), NVLink, and CrossFire allow multiple GPUs to draw images simultaneously for a single screen, increasing the processing power available for graphics.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] These technologies, however, are increasingly uncommon; most games do not fully use multiple GPUs, as most users cannot afford them.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Because GPU computations are memory-intensive, integrated processing may compete with the CPU for relatively slow system RAM, as it has minimal or no dedicated video memory.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] IGPUs use system memory with bandwidth up to a current maximum of 128 gigabytes per second, whereas a discrete graphics card may have a bandwidth of more than 1000 gigabytes per second between its video random access memory (VRAM) and GPU core.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] This memory bus bandwidth can limit the performance of the IGPU, though multi-channel memory can mitigate this deficiency.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] On systems with "Unified Memory Architecture" (UMA), including modern AMD processors with integrated graphics, modern Intel processors with integrated graphics, Apple processors, and modern consoles, the CPU cores and the GPU block share the same pool of RAM and memory address space.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] It is common to use a general purpose graphics processing unit (GPGPU) as a modified form of stream processor or a vector processor, running compute kernels.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] This turns the massive computational power of a modern graphics accelerator's shader pipeline into general-purpose computing power.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] In certain applications requiring massive vector operations, this can yield several orders of magnitude higher performance than a conventional CPU.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] The two largest discrete GPU designers, AMD and Nvidia, are pursuing this approach with an array of applications.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Nvidia and AMD collaborated with Stanford University to create a GPU-based client for the Folding@home distributed computing project for protein folding calculations.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] In certain circumstances, the GPU calculates forty times faster than the CPUs traditionally used by such applications.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] GPU-based high performance computers play a significant role in large-scale modelling.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Three of the ten most powerful supercomputers in the world take advantage of GPU acceleration.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Since 2005 there has been interest in using the performance offered by GPUs for evolutionary computation in general, and for accelerating the fitness evaluation in genetic programming in particular.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Most approaches compile linear or tree programs on the host PC and transfer the executable to the GPU to be run.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Typically a performance advantage is only obtained by running the single active program simultaneously on many example problems in parallel, using the GPU's single instruction, multiple data (SIMD) architecture.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Substantial acceleration can also be obtained by not compiling the programs, and instead transferring them to the GPU, to be interpreted there.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] A GPU can be attached to some external bus of a notebook.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] PCI Express is the only bus used for this purpose.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] The port may be, for example, an ExpressCard or mPCIe port (PCIe ×1, up to 5 or 2.5 gigabits per second respectively), a Thunderbolt 1, 2, or 3 port (PCIe ×4, up to 10, 20, or 40 gigabits per second respectively), a USB4 port with Thunderbolt compatibility, or an OCuLink port.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Those ports are only available on certain notebook systems. eGPU enclosures include their own power supply (PSU), because powerful GPUs can consume hundreds of watts.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Dedicated 3D graphics hardware dates back to graphic terminals such as the Adage AGT-30 from 1967 with analog matrix processors.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] In 1969 Evans & Sutherland (E&S) introduced the Line Drawing System-1 (LDS-1), which was the first all-digital system to provide matrix multiplication.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Also in 1969, the low-cost graphics terminal IMLAC PDS-1 was introduced.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] It later saw use as an early 3D gaming machine with the likes of Maze War.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] In the 1970s, the term "GPU" originally stood for graphics processor unit and described a programmable processing unit working independently from the CPU that was responsible for graphics manipulation and output.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] In professional hardware, in 1972 PLATO IV system becomes operational at the University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Between around 1973 and 1978, several networked multiplayer wireframe 3D games are implemented and popularized by users of the system.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Also in 1972, the E&S Continuous Tone 1 (CT1) "Watkins box" system (consisting of an E&S LDS-2 and Shaded Picture System) is delivered to Case Western Reserve University.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] It offered the first real-time Gouraud shading.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] In 1975, a joint effort between Evans & Sutherland Computer Corporation and the University of Utah's computer graphics department results in the first ever MOSFET video framebuffer, capable of color and smooth shading.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] E&S Continuous Tone 3 (CT3) system was delivered in 1977 to Lufthansa for pilot training using computer simulation.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] It was the first graphics system capable of real-time texture mapping.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Ikonas made graphics systems with 8- and 24-bit graphics and 3D acceleration in the late 70s.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Arcade system boards have used specialized 2D graphics circuits since the 1970s.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] In early video game hardware, RAM for frame buffers was expensive, so video chips composited data together as the display was being scanned out on the monitor.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] A specialized barrel shifter circuit helped the CPU animate the framebuffer graphics for various 1970s arcade video games from Midway and Taito, such as *Gun Fight* (1975), *Sea Wolf* (1976), and *Space Invaders* (1978).
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] The Namco Galaxian arcade system in 1979 used specialized graphics hardware that supported RGB color, multi-colored sprites, and tilemap backgrounds.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] The Galaxian hardware was widely used during the golden age of arcade video games, by game companies such as Namco, Centuri, Gremlin, Irem, Konami, Midway, Nichibutsu, Sega, and Taito.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] The Atari 2600 in 1977 used a video shifter called the Television Interface Adaptor.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Atari 8-bit computers (1979) had ANTIC, a video processor which interpreted instructions describing a "display list"—the way the scan lines map to specific bitmapped or character modes and where the memory is stored (so there did not need to be a contiguous frame buffer).
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] 6502 machine code subroutines could be triggered on scan lines by setting a bit on a display list instruction.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] ANTIC also supported smooth vertical and horizontal scrolling independent of the CPU.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] In the 1980s significant advancements were made in professional 3D graphics hardware.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Perhaps most impactful was the 1981 development of the Geometry Engine, a VLSI vector processor ASIC designed by Jim Clark and Marc Hannah at Stanford University.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] This processor is the forerunner of modern tensor cores and other similar processors marketed for graphics and AI.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] The Geometry Engine went on to be used in Silicon Graphics workstations for many years.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Silicon Graphics's first product, shipped in November 1983, was the IRIS 1000, a terminal with hardware-accelerated 3D graphics based on the Geometry Engine.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] The Geometry Engine was capable of approximately 6 million operations per second.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] The 1981 NEC μPD7220 was the first implementation of a personal computer graphics display processor as a single large-scale integration (LSI) integrated circuit chip.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] This enabled the design of low-cost, high-performance video graphics cards such as those from Number Nine Visual Technology.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] It became the best-known GPU until the mid-1980s.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] It was the first fully integrated VLSI (very large-scale integration) metal–oxide–semiconductor (NMOS) graphics display processor for PCs, supported up to 1024×1024 resolution, and laid the foundations for the PC graphics market.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] It was used in a number of graphics cards and was licensed for clones such as the Intel 82720, the first of Intel's graphics processing units.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] The Williams Electronics arcade games *Robotron: 2084*, *Joust*, *Sinistar*, and *Bubbles*, all released in 1982, contain custom blitter chips for operating on 16-color bitmaps.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] In 1984, Hitachi released the ARTC HD63484, the first major CMOS graphics processor for personal computers.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] The ARTC could display up to 4K resolution when in monochrome mode.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] It was used in a number of graphics cards and terminals during the late 1980s.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] In 1985, the Amiga was released with a custom graphics chip called Agnus including a blitter for bitmap manipulation, line drawing, and area fill.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] It also included a coprocessor with its own simple instruction set, that was capable of manipulating graphics hardware registers in sync with the video beam (e.g. for per-scanline palette switches, sprite multiplexing, and hardware windowing), or driving the blitter.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Also in 1985, IBM released the Professional Graphics Controller, designed by later to be Nvidia co-founder Curtis Priem, which was a rudimentary 3D card with 640 × 480 256-color graphics which used a dedicated CPU to draw graphics independently of the main system.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] It was used as the basis of cards by a number of makers (including Matrox) and its analog RGB signaling led directly to the VGA video standard.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Priem later in the 80s worked on the influential Sun Microsystems GX (also known as cgsix) accelerated 2D graphics card.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] In 1986, Texas Instruments released the TMS34010, the first fully programmable graphics processor.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] It could run general-purpose code but also had a graphics-oriented instruction set.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] During 1990–1992, this chip became the basis of the Texas Instruments Graphics Architecture ("TIGA") Windows accelerator cards.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Following in 1987, the IBM 8514 graphics system was released.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] It was one of the first video cards for IBM PC compatibles that implemented fixed-function 2D primitives in electronic hardware.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Sharp's X68000, released in 1987, used a custom graphics chipset with a 65,536 color palette and hardware support for sprites, scrolling, and multiple playfields.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] It served as a development machine for Capcom's CP System arcade board.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Fujitsu's FM Towns computer, released in 1989, had support for a 16,777,216 color palette.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] For context, IBM also introduced its Video Graphics Array (VGA) display system in 1987, with a maximum resolution of 640 × 480 pixels.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Unlike 8514/A, VGA had no hardware acceleration features.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] In November 1988, NEC Home Electronics announced its creation of the Video Electronics Standards Association (VESA) to develop and promote a Super VGA (SVGA) computer display standard as a successor to VGA.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Super VGA enabled graphics display resolutions up to 800 × 600 pixels, a 56% increase.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] In 1988 SGI sold IRIS workstation graphics with 10-12 Geometry Engines and introduced the IrisVision add-in board for IBM MicroChannel bus (RS/6000) based on the Geometry Engine as well.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] In 1988 as well, the first dedicated polygonal 3D graphics boards in arcade machines were introduced with the Namco System 21 and Taito Air System.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] The 1990s again saw considerable advancements in professional workstation 3D graphics hardware from Sun Microsystems, SGI, and others.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] The introduction of OpenGL by SGI in 1992 paved the way for standard hardware-independent 3D programming interfaces.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] However, by the mid and late 90s, professional hardware was being slowly eclipsed by consumer products which offered similar or even better performance, especially in regards to texture mapping, at a lower cost and on platforms familiar to end users.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] In 1991, S3 Graphics introduced the *S3 86C911*, which its designers named after the Porsche 911 as an indication of the performance increase it promised.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] The 86C911 spawned a variety of imitators: by 1995, all major PC graphics chip makers had added 2D acceleration support to their chips.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Fixed-function *Windows accelerators* surpassed expensive general-purpose graphics coprocessors in Windows performance, and such coprocessors faded from the PC market.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] In the early- and mid-1990s, real-time 3D graphics became increasingly common in arcade, computer, and console games, which led to increasing public demand for hardware-accelerated 3D graphics.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Early examples of mass-market 3D graphics hardware can be found in arcade system boards such as the Sega Model 1, Namco System 22, and Sega Model 2, and the fifth-generation video game consoles such as the Saturn, PlayStation, and Nintendo 64.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Arcade systems such as the Sega Model 2 and SGI Onyx-based Namco Magic Edge Hornet Simulator in 1993 were capable of hardware T&L (transform, clipping, and lighting) years before appearing in consumer graphics cards.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] In 1994, Sony used the term GPU (with the meaning graphics processing unit) in reference to the PlayStation console's Toshiba-designed Sony GPU.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Another early example is the Super FX chip, a RISC-based on-cartridge graphics chip used in some SNES games, notably *Doom* and *Star Fox*.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Some systems used DSPs to accelerate transformations.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Fujitsu, which worked on the Sega Model 2 arcade system, began working on integrating T&L into a single LSI solution for use in home computers in 1995; the Fujitsu Pinolite, the first 3D geometry processor for personal computers, announced in 1997.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] The first hardware T&L GPU on home video game consoles was the Nintendo 64's Reality Coprocessor, released in 1996.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] In 1997, Mitsubishi released the 3Dpro/2MP, a GPU capable of transformation and lighting, for workstations and Windows NT desktops; ATi used it for its FireGL 4000 graphics card, released in 1997.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] The term "GPU" was coined by Sony in reference to the 32-bit Sony GPU (designed by Toshiba) in the PlayStation video game console, released in 1994.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Pixel shading is often used for bump mapping, which adds texture to make an object look shiny, dull, rough, or even round or extruded.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] With the introduction of the Nvidia GeForce 8 series and new generic stream processing units, GPUs became more generalized computing devices.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] GPGPUs were the precursors to what is now called a compute shader (e.g.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] CUDA, OpenCL, DirectCompute) and actually abused the hardware to a degree by treating the data passed to algorithms as texture maps and executing algorithms by drawing a triangle or quad with an appropriate pixel shader.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] This entails some overheads since units like the scan converter are involved where they are not needed (nor are triangle manipulations even a concern—except to invoke the pixel shader).
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Nvidia's CUDA platform, first introduced in 2007, was the earliest widely adopted programming model for GPU computing.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] OpenCL is an open standard defined by the Khronos Group that allows for the development of code for both GPUs and CPUs with an emphasis on portability.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] OpenCL solutions are supported by Intel, AMD, Nvidia, and ARM, and according to a report in 2011 by Evans Data, OpenCL had become the second most popular HPC tool.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] In 2010, Nvidia partnered with Audi to power their cars' dashboards, using the Tegra GPU to provide increased functionality to cars' navigation and entertainment systems.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Advances in GPU technology in cars helped advance self-driving technology.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] AMD's Radeon HD 6000 series cards were released in 2010, and in 2011 AMD released its 6000M Series discrete GPUs for mobile devices.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] The Kepler line of graphics cards by Nvidia were released in 2012 and were used in the Nvidia 600 and 700 series cards.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] A feature in this GPU microarchitecture included GPU boost, a technology that adjusts the clock-speed of a video card to increase or decrease according to its power draw.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Kepler also introduced NVENC video encoding acceleration technology.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] The PS4 and Xbox One were released in 2013; they both used GPUs based on AMD's Radeon HD 7850 and 7790.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Nvidia's Kepler line of GPUs was followed by the Maxwell line, manufactured on the same process.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Nvidia's 28 nm chips were manufactured by TSMC in Taiwan using the 28 nm process.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Compared to the 40 nm technology from the past, this manufacturing process allowed a 20 percent boost in performance while drawing less power.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Virtual reality headsets have high system requirements; manufacturers recommended the GTX 970 and the R9 290X or better at the time of their release.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Cards based on the Pascal microarchitecture were released in 2016.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] The GeForce 10 series of cards are of this generation of graphics cards.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] They are made using the 16 nm manufacturing process which improves upon previous microarchitectures.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] In 2018, Nvidia launched the RTX 20 series GPUs that added ray tracing cores to GPUs, allowing real time ray tracing to be performant on mass market hardware.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Polaris 11 and Polaris 10 GPUs from AMD are fabricated by a 14 nm process.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Their release resulted in a substantial increase in the performance per watt of AMD video cards.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] AMD also released the Vega GPU series for the high end market as a competitor to Nvidia's high end Pascal cards, also featuring HBM2 like the Titan V.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] In 2019, AMD released the successor to their Graphics Core Next (GCN) microarchitecture/instruction set.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Dubbed RDNA, the first product featuring it was the Radeon RX 5000 series of video cards.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] The company announced that the successor to the RDNA microarchitecture would be incremental (a "refresh").
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] AMD unveiled the Radeon RX 6000 series, its RDNA 2 graphics cards with support for hardware-accelerated ray tracing.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] The product series, launched in late 2020, consisted of the RX 6800, RX 6800 XT, and RX 6900 XT.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] The RX 6700 XT, which is based on Navi 22, was launched in early 2021.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] The PlayStation 5 and Xbox Series X and Series S were released in 2020; they both use GPUs based on the RDNA 2 microarchitecture with incremental improvements and different GPU configurations in each system's implementation.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] In the 2020s, GPUs have been increasingly used for calculations involving embarrassingly parallel problems, such as training of neural networks on enormous datasets that are needed for artificial intelligence large language models.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Specialized processing cores on most modern GPUs that are dedicated to deep learning provide significant FLOPS performance increases, using 4×4 matrix multiplication and division.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Early implementations, such as Nvidia's Volta microarchitecture, released in 2017, saw results of up to 128 TFLOPS in some applications.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Since then, AI acceleration cores have been a widely adopted feature in consumer and workstation microarchitectures starting with Nvidia's Turing microarchitecture in 2018, named Tensor cores.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] AMD originally implemented their equivalent "Matrix" Cores for consumers in their RDNA 3 architecture - however RDNA 4's Matrix Cores were the first to introduce FP8 acceleration - which is required to run the full FSR Redstone feature set such as Machine Learning Upscaling and Frame Generation.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] However, community made hacks on both Linux and Windows have allowed RDNA 2, 3, and competitor GPUs to run a weaker version of FSR 4 known as FSR 4 INT8.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] The PlayStation 5 Pro, launched in 2024, has customized Machine Learning cores - which focus solely on INT8 acceleration - based on RDNA 4's for PlayStation Spectral Super Resolution to enhance framerates and image quality.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Intel has implemented their equivalent "XMX" Cores in all of their Arc GPUs, starting with the Alchemist microarchitecture.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] This is used for XeSS (Xe Super Sampling), XeFG (Xe Frame Generation), and more.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] Ray tracing has also been incredibly prevalent in the 2020s with some games, such as DOOM: The Dark Ages, requiring a hardware ray tracing capable GPU to even start.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] While it does lead to worse performance and less overall accessibility, id software claimed this saved several man hours and shrinked the game by over 100 gigabytes due to the game being entirely built around ray tracing .
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] In 2013, 438.3 million GPUs were shipped globally and the forecast for 2014 was 414.2 million.
[src:dearpygui/graphics-processing-unit] However, by the third quarter of 2022, shipments of PC GPUs totaled around 75.5 million units, down 19% year-over-year.
[src:dearpygui/immediate-mode-gui] without the use of extensive indirection – thus***immediate***– to retained resources.
[src:dearpygui/immediate-mode-gui] It does not preclude the use of double-buffering.
[src:dearpygui/immediate-mode-gui] Retained mode is an alternative approach.
[src:dearpygui/immediate-mode-gui] Historically, retained mode has been the dominant style in GUI libraries; however, both can coexist in the same library and are not necessarily exclusive in practice.
[src:dearpygui/immediate-mode-gui] In immediate mode, the scene (complete object model of the rendering primitives) is retained in the memory space of the client, instead of the graphics library.
[src:dearpygui/immediate-mode-gui] This implies that in an immediate mode application, the lists of graphical objects to be rendered are kept by the client and are not saved by the graphics library API.
[src:dearpygui/immediate-mode-gui] The application must re-issue all drawing commands required to describe the entire scene each time a new frame is required, regardless of actual changes.
[src:dearpygui/immediate-mode-gui] This method provides on the one hand a maximum of control and flexibility to the application program, but on the other hand it also generates continuous work load on the CPU.
[src:dearpygui/immediate-mode-gui] Examples of immediate mode rendering systems include Direct2D, OpenGL and Quartz.
[src:dearpygui/immediate-mode-gui] There are some immediate mode GUIs that are particularly suitable when used in conjunction with immediate mode rendering systems.
[src:dearpygui/immediate-mode-gui] Primitive vertex attribute data may be inserted frame by frame into a command buffer by a rendering API.
[src:dearpygui/immediate-mode-gui] This involves significant bandwidth and processor time (especially if the graphics processing unit is on a separate bus), but may be advantageous for data generated dynamically by the CPU.
[src:dearpygui/immediate-mode-gui] It is less common since the advent of increasingly versatile shaders, with which a graphics processing unit may generate increasingly complex effects without the need for CPU intervention.
[src:dearpygui/immediate-mode-gui] Graphical user interfaces traditionally use retained mode-style API design, but immediate mode GUIs instead use an immediate mode-style API design, in which user code directly specifies the GUI elements to draw in the user input loop.
[src:dearpygui/immediate-mode-gui] For example, rather than having a CreateButton() function that a user would call once to instantiate a button, an immediate-mode GUI API may have a DoButton() function which should be called whenever the button should be on screen.
[src:dearpygui/immediate-mode-gui] The technique was developed by Casey Muratori in 2002.
[src:dearpygui/immediate-mode-gui] Prominent implementations include Omar Cornut's Dear ImGui in C++, Nic Barker's Clay in C and Micha Mettke's Nuklear in C.
[src:dearpygui/language-binding] In programming and software design, a **binding** is an application programming interface (API) that provides glue code specifically made to allow a programming language to use a foreign library or operating system service (one that is not native to that language).
[src:dearpygui/language-binding] Binding generally refers to a mapping of one thing to another.
[src:dearpygui/language-binding] In the context of software libraries, bindings are wrapper libraries that bridge two programming languages, so that a library written for one language can be used in another language.
[src:dearpygui/language-binding] Many software libraries are written in system programming languages such as C or C++.
[src:dearpygui/language-binding] To use such libraries from another language, usually of higher-level, such as Java, Common Lisp, Scheme, Python, or Lua, a binding to the library must be created in that language, possibly requiring recompiling the language's code, depending on the amount of modification needed.
[src:dearpygui/language-binding] However, most languages offer a foreign function interface, such as Python's and OCaml's `ctypes`, and Embeddable Common Lisp's `cffi` and `uffi`.
[src:dearpygui/language-binding] For example, Python bindings are used when an extant C library, written for some purpose, is to be used from Python.
[src:dearpygui/language-binding] Another example is `libsvn` which is written in C to provide an API to access the Subversion software repository.
[src:dearpygui/language-binding] To access Subversion from within Java code, `libsvnjavahl` can be used, which depends on `libsvn` being installed and acts as a bridge between the language Java and `libsvn`, thus providing an API that invokes functions from `libsvn` to do the work.
[src:dearpygui/language-binding] Major motives to create library bindings include software reuse, to reduce reimplementing a library in several languages, and the difficulty of implementing some algorithms efficiently in some high-level languages.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Guido van Rossum began working on Python in the late 1980s as a successor to the ABC programming language.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Python 3.0, released in 2008, was a major revision and not completely backward-compatible with earlier versions.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Beginning with Python 3.5, capabilities and keywords for typing were added to the language, allowing optional static typing.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] As of 2026, the Python Software Foundation supports Python 3.10, 3.11, 3.12, 3.13, and 3.14, following the project's annual release cycle and five-year support policy.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Python 3.15 is currently in the beta development phase, and the stable release is expected to launch in October 2026.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Earlier versions in the 3.x series have reached end-of-life and no longer receive security updates.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Python has gained extensive use in the machine learning community.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] It is widely taught as an introductory programming language.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Since 2003, Python has consistently ranked among the top ten most popular programming languages in the TIOBE Programming Community Index, which ranks programming languages based on searches across 24 platforms.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Python was conceived in the late 1980s by Guido van Rossum at Centrum Wiskunde & Informatica (CWI) in the Netherlands.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] It was designed as a successor to the ABC programming language, which was inspired by SETL, capable of exception handling and interfacing with the Amoeba operating system.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Python implementation began in December 1989.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Van Rossum first released it in 1991 as Python 0.9.0.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] In January 2019, active Python core developers elected a five-member Steering Council to lead the project.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] The name *Python* derives from the British comedy series *Monty Python's Flying Circus*.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Python 2.0 was released on 16 October 2000, featuring many new features such as list comprehensions, cycle-detecting garbage collection, reference counting, and Unicode support.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Python 2.7's end-of-life was initially set for 2015, and then postponed to 2020 out of concern that a large body of existing code could not easily be forward-ported to Python 3.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] It no longer receives security patches or updates.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] While Python 2.7 and older versions are officially unsupported, a different unofficial Python implementation, PyPy, continues to support Python 2, i.e., "2.7.18+" (plus 3.11), with the plus signifying (at least some) "backported security updates".
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Python 3.0 was released on 3 December 2008, and was a major revision and not completely backward-compatible with earlier versions, with some new semantics and changed syntax.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Python 2.7.18, released in 2020, was the last release of Python 2.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Several releases in the Python 3.x series have added new syntax to the language, and made a few (considered very minor) backward-incompatible changes.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] As of May 2026, Python 3.14.6 is the latest stable release.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] All older 3.x versions had a security update down to Python 3.9.24 then again with 3.9.25, the final version in 3.9 series.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Python 3.10 is, since November 2025, the oldest supported branch.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Python 3.15 has an alpha released, and Android has an official downloadable executable available for Python 3.14.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Releases receive two years of full support followed by three years of security support.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Python is a multi-paradigm programming language.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Object-oriented programming and structured programming are fully supported, and many of their features support functional programming and aspect-oriented programming – including metaprogramming and metaobjects.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Many other paradigms are supported via extensions, including design by contract and logic programming.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Python is often referred to as a *'glue language'* because it is purposely designed to be able to integrate components written in other languages.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Python uses dynamic typing and a combination of reference counting and a cycle-detecting garbage collector for memory management.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] It uses dynamic name resolution (late binding), which binds method and variable names during program execution.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Python's design offers some support for functional programming in the "Lisp tradition".
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] It has `filter`, `map`, and `reduce` functions; list comprehensions, dictionaries, sets, and generator expressions.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] The standard library has two modules (`itertools` and `functools`) that implement functional tools borrowed from Haskell and Standard ML.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] However, Python has received criticism for violating these principles and adding unnecessary language bloat.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Responses to these criticisms note that the Zen of Python is a guideline rather than a rule.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] The addition of some new features had been controversial: Guido van Rossum resigned as *Benevolent Dictator for Life* after conflict about adding the assignment expression operator in Python 3.8.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Nevertheless, rather than building all functionality into its core, Python was designed to be highly extensible through modules.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] This compact modularity has made it particularly popular as a means of adding programmable interfaces to existing applications.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Van Rossum's vision of a small core language with a large standard library and an easily extensible interpreter stemmed from his frustrations with ABC, which represented the opposite approach.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Python claims to strive for a simpler, less-cluttered syntax and grammar, while giving developers a choice in their coding methodology.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Python lacks `do .. while` loops, which Rossum considered harmful.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] In contrast to Perl's motto "there is more than one way to do it", Python advocates an approach where "there should be one – and preferably only one – obvious way to do it".
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] In practice, however, Python provides many ways to achieve a given goal.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] There are at least three ways to format a string literal, with no certainty as to which one a programmer should use.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Python's developers typically prioritize readability over performance.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] For example, they reject patches to non-critical parts of the CPython reference implementation that would offer increases in speed that do not justify the cost of clarity and readability.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Execution speed can be improved by moving speed-critical functions to extension modules written in languages such as C, or by using a just-in-time compiler like PyPy.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Also, it is possible to transpile to other languages.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] However, this approach either fails to achieve the expected speed-up, since Python is a very dynamic language, or only a restricted subset of Python is compiled (with potential minor semantic changes).
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Python is meant to be a fun language to use.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] This goal is reflected in the name – a tribute to the British comedy group Monty Python – and in playful approaches to some tutorials and reference materials.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] For instance, some code examples use the terms "spam" and "eggs" (in reference to a Monty Python sketch), rather than the typical terms "foo" and "bar".
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] A common neologism in the Python community is *pythonic*, which has a broad range of meanings related to program style: Pythonic code may use Python idioms well; be natural or show fluency in the language; or conform with Python's minimalist philosophy and emphasis on readability.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] There are 3 kinds of PEPs, with those are being *standards track PEP*, *Informational PEP* and *Process PEP*s which has their own unique meanings.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] They were firstly introduced in 2000, inspired by other RfCs (requests for comments) and Desing Enhancement Proposals.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Most known PEPs are PEP – 1, PEP – 8, PEP – 20, PEP – 257 and others.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Python is meant to be an easily readable language.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Its formatting is visually uncluttered and often uses English keywords where other languages use punctuation.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Unlike many other languages, it does not use curly brackets to delimit blocks, and semicolons after statements are allowed but rarely used.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] It has fewer syntactic exceptions and special cases than C or Pascal.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Python uses whitespace indentation, rather than curly brackets or keywords, to delimit blocks.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] An increase in indentation comes after certain statements; a decrease in indentation signifies the end of the current block.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Thus, the program's visual structure accurately represents its semantic structure.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] This feature is sometimes termed the off-side rule.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Some other languages use indentation this way; but in most, indentation has no semantic meaning.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] The recommended indent size is four spaces.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] The assignment statement (`=`) binds a name as a reference to a separate, dynamically allocated object.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Variables may subsequently be rebound at any time to any object.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] In Python, a variable name is a generic reference holder without a fixed data type; however, it always refers to *some* object with a type.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] This is called dynamic typing—in contrast to statically-typed languages, where each variable may contain only a value of a certain type.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Python does not support tail call optimization or first-class continuations; according to Van Rossum, the language never will.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] However, better support for coroutine-like functionality is provided by extending Python's generators.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Before 2.5, generators were lazy iterators; data was passed unidirectionally out of the generator.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] From Python 2.5 on, it is possible to pass data back into a generator function; and from version 3.3, data can be passed through multiple stack levels.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] In Python, a distinction between expressions and statements is rigidly enforced, in contrast to languages such as Common Lisp, Scheme, or Ruby.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] A statement cannot be part of an expression; because of this restriction, expressions such as list and `dict` comprehensions (and lambda expressions) cannot contain statements.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] As a particular case, an assignment statement such as `a = 1` cannot be part of the conditional expression of a conditional statement.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Python uses duck typing, and it has typed objects but untyped variable names.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Type constraints are not checked at definition time; rather, operations on an object may fail at usage time, indicating that the object is not of an appropriate type.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Despite being dynamically typed, Python is strongly typed, forbidding operations that are poorly defined (e.g., adding a number and a string) rather than quietly attempting to interpret them.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Python allows programmers to define their own types using classes, most often for object-oriented programming.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] New instances of classes are constructed by calling the class, for example, `SpamClass()` or `EggsClass()`); the classes are instances of the metaclass `type` (which is an instance of itself), thereby allowing metaprogramming and reflection.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Before version 3.0, Python had two kinds of classes, both using the same syntax: *old-style* and *new-style*.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Current Python versions support the semantics of only the new style.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Python supports optional type annotations.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] These annotations are not enforced by the language, but may be used by external tools such as **mypy** to catch errors.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Python includes a module `typing` including several type names for type annotations.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Also, mypy supports a Python compiler called mypyc, which leverages type annotations for optimization.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Python includes conventional symbols for arithmetic operators (`+`, `-`, `*`, `/`), the floor-division operator `//`, and the modulo operator `%`.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] (With the modulo operator, a remainder can be negative, e.g., `4 % -3 == -2`.) Python also offers the `**` symbol for exponentiation, e.g.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] These operators work as in traditional mathematics; with the same precedence rules, the infix operators `+` and `-` can also be unary, to represent positive and negative numbers respectively.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Division between integers produces floating-point results.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] In Python terms, the `/` operator represents *true division* (or simply *division*), while the `//` operator represents *floor division.* Before version 3.0, the `/` operator represents *classic division*.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Rounding towards negative infinity, though a different method than in most languages, adds consistency to Python.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] For instance, this rounding implies that the equation `(a + b)//b == a//b + 1` is always true.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Also, the rounding implies that the equation `b*(a//b) + a%b == a` is valid for both positive and negative values of `a`.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] As expected, the result of `a%b` lies in the half-open interval [0, *b*), where `b` is a positive integer; however, maintaining the validity of the equation requires that the result must lie in the interval (*b*, 0] when `b` is negative.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Python provides a `round` function for rounding a float to the nearest integer.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] For tie-breaking, Python 3 uses the *round to even* method: `round(1.5)` and `round(2.5)` both produce `2`.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Python allows Boolean expressions that contain multiple equality relations to be consistent with general usage in mathematics.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] For example, the expression `a < b < c` tests whether `a` is less than `b` and `b` is less than `c`.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] C-derived languages interpret this expression differently: in C, the expression would first evaluate `a < b`, resulting in 0 or 1, and that result would then be compared with `c`.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Python uses arbitrary-precision arithmetic for all integer operations.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] The `Decimal` type/class in the `decimal` module provides decimal floating-point numbers to a pre-defined arbitrary precision with several rounding modes.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] The `Fraction` class in the `fractions` module provides arbitrary precision for rational numbers.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Due to Python's extensive mathematics library and the third-party library NumPy, the language is frequently used for scientific scripting in tasks such as numerical data processing and manipulation.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Functions are created in Python by using the `def` keyword.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] A function is defined similarly to how it is called, by first providing the function name and then the required parameters.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] To assign a default value to a function parameter in case no actual value is provided at run time, variable-definition syntax can be used inside the function header.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Python's large standard library is commonly cited as one of its greatest strengths.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] For Internet-facing applications, many standard formats and protocols such as MIME and HTTP are supported.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] The language includes modules for creating graphical user interfaces, connecting to relational databases, generating pseudorandom numbers, arithmetic with arbitrary-precision decimals, manipulating regular expressions, and unit testing.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Some parts of the standard library are covered by specifications—for example, the Web Server Gateway Interface (WSGI) implementation `wsgiref` follows PEP 333—but most parts are specified by their code, internal documentation, and test suites.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] However, because most of the standard library is cross-platform Python code, only a few modules must be altered or rewritten for variant implementations.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] As of 13 March 2025, the Python Package Index (PyPI), the official repository for third-party Python software, contains over 614,339 packages.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Most Python implementations (including CPython) include a read–eval–print loop (REPL); this permits the environment to function as a command line interpreter, with which users enter statements sequentially and receive results immediately.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Also, CPython is bundled with an integrated development environment (IDE) called IDLE, which is oriented toward beginners.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Other shells, including IDLE and IPython, add additional capabilities such as improved auto-completion, session-state retention, and syntax highlighting.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] CPython is the reference implementation of Python.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] This implementation is written in C, meeting the C11 standard since version 3.11.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Older versions use the C89 standard with several select C99 features, but third-party extensions are not limited to older C versions—e.g., they can be implemented using C11 or C++.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] CPython compiles Python programs into an intermediate bytecode, which is then executed by a virtual machine.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] CPython is distributed with a large standard library written in a combination of C and native Python.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] CPython is available for many platforms, including Windows and most modern Unix-like systems, including macOS (and Apple M1 Macs, since Python 3.9.1, using an experimental installer).
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Starting with Python 3.9, the Python installer intentionally fails to install on Windows 7 and 8; Windows XP was supported until Python 3.5.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Old Python versions unofficially support VMS (mostly supporting) and OpenVMS x86-64 has Python 3.10 support.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Platform portability was one of Python's earliest priorities.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] During development of Python 1 and 2, even OS/2 and Solaris were supported; since that time, support has been dropped for many platforms.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] All current Python versions (since 3.7) support only operating systems that feature multithreading, by now supporting not nearly as many operating systems (dropping many outdated) than in the past.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] All alternative implementations have at least slightly different semantics.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] For example, an alternative may include unordered dictionaries, in contrast to other current Python versions.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] As another example in the larger Python ecosystem, PyPy does not support the full C Python API.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Creating an executable with Python often is done by bundling an entire Python interpreter into the executable, which causes binary sizes to be massive for small programs, yet there exist implementations that are capable of truly compiling Python.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Stackless Python is a significant fork of CPython that implements microthreads.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] This implementation uses the call stack differently, thus allowing massively concurrent programs.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] A performance comparison among various Python implementations, using a non-numerical (combinatorial) workload, was presented at EuroSciPy '13.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] In addition, Python's performance relative to other programming languages is benchmarked by The Computer Language Benchmarks Game.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] There are several approaches to optimizing Python performance, despite the inherent slowness of an interpreted language.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Python's development is conducted mostly through the *Python Enhancement Proposal* (PEP) process; this process is the primary mechanism for proposing major new features, collecting community input on issues, and documenting Python design decisions.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Python coding style is covered in PEP 8.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Outstanding PEPs are reviewed and commented on by the Python community and the steering council.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Enhancement of the language corresponds with development of the CPython reference implementation.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] The mailing list python-dev is the primary forum for the language's development.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Specific issues were originally discussed in the Roundup bug tracker hosted by the foundation.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] In 2022, all issues and discussions were migrated to GitHub.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Development originally took place on a self-hosted source-code repository running Mercurial, until Python moved to GitHub in January 2017.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Many alpha, beta, and release-candidates are also released as previews and for testing before final releases.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Although there is a rough schedule for releases, they are often delayed if the code is not ready yet.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Python's development team monitors the state of the code by running a large unit test suite during development.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] The major academic conference on Python is PyCon.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Also, there are special Python mentoring programs, such as PyLadies.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Python's name is inspired by the British comedy group Monty Python, whom Python creator Guido van Rossum enjoyed while developing the language.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Monty Python references appear frequently in Python code and culture; for example, the metasyntactic variables often used in Python literature are *spam* and *eggs*, rather than the traditional *foo* and *bar*.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Also, the official Python documentation contains various references to Monty Python routines.
[src:dearpygui/python-programming-language] Python users are sometimes referred to as "Pythonistas".
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In a computer graphics context, in standard usage, the word "rendering" by itself means rendering 3D scenes, but it is sometimes used with a broader meaning.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A modifier such as "2D" or "3D" is used when there is potential ambiguity (e.g.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A software application or component that performs rendering is called a **rendering engine**, **render engine**, **rendering system**, **graphics engine**, or simply a **renderer**.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A distinction is made between real-time rendering, in which images are generated and displayed immediately (ideally fast enough to give the impression of motion or animation), and offline rendering (sometimes called pre-rendering) in which images or film frames, are generated for later viewing.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Offline rendering can use a slower and higher-quality renderer.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Interactive applications such as games must primarily use real-time rendering, although they may incorporate pre-rendered content.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Rendering produces images of scenes or objects defined using coordinates in 3D space, seen from a particular viewpoint.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] It uses knowledge and ideas from optics, the study of visual perception, mathematics, and software engineering, and it has applications such as video games, simulators, visual effects for films and television, design visualization, and medical diagnosis.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Realistic rendering requires modeling the propagation of light in an environment, e.g. by applying the rendering equation.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Real-time rendering uses high-performance *rasterization* algorithms that process a list of shapes and determine which pixels are covered by each shape.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] When more realism is required (e.g. for architectural visualization or visual effects) slower pixel-by-pixel algorithms such as *ray tracing* are used instead.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] (Ray tracing can also be used selectively during rasterized rendering to improve the realism of lighting and reflections.) A type of ray tracing called *path tracing* is currently the most common technique for photorealistic rendering.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Path tracing is also popular for generating high-quality non-photorealistic images, such as frames for 3D animated films.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Both rasterization and ray tracing can be sped up ("accelerated") by specially designed microprocessors called GPUs.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Rasterization algorithms are also used to produce images containing only 2D shapes such as polygons and text.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] This type of rendering is sometimes called *2D rendering*, and its applications include digital illustration, graphic design, 2D animation, desktop publishing and the display of user interfaces.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Historically, rendering was called **image synthesis** but today this term is likely to mean AI image generation.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The term "neural rendering" is sometimes used when a neural network is the primary means of generating an image but some degree of control over the output image is provided.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Neural networks can also assist rendering without replacing traditional algorithms, e.g. by removing noise from path traced images.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A large proportion of computer graphics research has worked towards producing images that resemble photographs.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Fundamental techniques that make this possible were invented in the 1980s, but at the end of the decade, photorealism for complex scenes was still considered a distant goal.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Today, photorealism is routinely achievable for offline rendering, but remains difficult for real-time rendering.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In order to produce realistic images, rendering must simulate how light travels from light sources, is reflected, refracted, and scattered (often many times) by objects in the scene, passes through a camera lens, and finally reaches the film or sensor of the camera.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The physics used in these simulations is primarily geometrical optics, in which particles of light follow (usually straight) lines called *rays*, but in some situations (such as when rendering thin films, like the surface of soap bubbles) the wave nature of light must be taken into account.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In realistic scenes, objects are illuminated both by light that arrives directly from a light source (after passing mostly unimpeded through air), and light that has bounced off other objects in the scene.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The simulation of this complex lighting is called global illumination.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In the past, indirect lighting was often faked (especially when rendering animated films) by placing additional hidden lights in the scene, but today path tracing is used to render it accurately.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] For true photorealism, the camera used to take the photograph must be simulated.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The *thin lens approximation* allows combining perspective projection with depth of field (and bokeh) emulation.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Camera lens simulations can be made more realistic by modeling the way light is refracted by the components of the lens.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Motion blur is often simulated if film or video frames are being rendered.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Simulated lens flare and bloom are sometimes added to make the image appear subjectively brighter (although the design of real cameras tries to reduce these effects).
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Realistic rendering uses mathematical descriptions of how different surface materials reflect light, called *reflectance models* or (when physically plausible) *bidirectional reflectance distribution functions (BRDFs)*.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Rendering materials such as marble, plant leaves, and human skin requires simulating an effect called subsurface scattering, in which a portion of the light travels into the material, is scattered, and then travels back out again.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The way color, and properties such as roughness, vary over a surface can be represented efficiently using texture mapping.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] For some applications (including early stages of 3D modeling), simplified rendering styles such as wireframe rendering may be appropriate, particularly when the material and surface details have not been defined and only the shape of an object is known.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Games and other real-time applications may use simpler and less realistic rendering techniques as an artistic or design choice, or to allow higher frame rates on lower-end hardware.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Orthographic and isometric projections can be used for a stylized effect or to ensure that parallel lines are depicted as parallel in CAD rendering.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Non-photorealistic rendering (NPR) uses techniques like edge detection and posterization to produce 3D images that resemble technical illustrations, cartoons, or other styles of drawing or painting.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In 2D computer graphics the positions and sizes of shapes are specified using 2D coordinates (x and y) instead of 3D coordinates (x, y, and z).
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] 2D rendering APIs often use a resolution-independent coordinate system, with a viewport determining how to convert coordinates to pixel indexes called *device coordinates*.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Transformations such as scaling, translation, and rotation may be applied before rendering the shapes.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] These affine transformations are often represented by 3 × 3 matrices, allowing easier composition of transformations.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Higher-quality 2D rendering engines such as SVG renderers usually implement anti-aliasing to reduce the jagged appearance of rasterized lines and shape edges.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] When rendering overlapping shapes, renderers commonly use a "painter's model" in which the shapes are drawn in some determined order, or their contributions to each pixel are composited using blending operations that may depend on the order of the inputs.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Renderers may allow giving shapes a "z index" or "stacking order" to specify the rendering or blending order (unlike the z coordinate used in 3D rendering, this third coordinate only indicates an order, not a distance, and cannot be meaningfully rotated together with the x and y coordinates).
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] 2D rendering typically does not simulate light propagation (which would likely require specifying 3D positions or thickness for the shapes).
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Effects such as drop shadows and transparency are defined by mathematical functions with no physical basis.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] 2D rendering for print output may need to support very high resolutions, e.g.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] 600 or 1200 DPI for a typical laser printer, or 2400 DPI or higher for an imagesetter or platesetter.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Grayscale and color images require halftones (or some form of dithering or stochastic screening) and color separations.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A rendering engine called a *raster image processor* (RIP) converts input data such as PDF files into the high-resolution bitmap images used by the printer.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Before a 3D scene or 2D image can be rendered, it must be described in a way that the rendering software can understand.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Historically, inputs for both 2D and 3D rendering were usually text files, which are easier than binary files for humans to edit and debug.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Traditional rendering algorithms use geometric descriptions of 3D scenes or 2D images.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Applications and algorithms that render visualizations of data scanned from the real world, or scientific simulations, may require different types of input data.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The PostScript format (which is often credited with the rise of desktop publishing) provides a standardized, interoperable way to describe 2D graphics and page layout.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The Scalable Vector Graphics (SVG) format is also text-based, and the PDF format uses the PostScript language internally.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Many file formats exist for storing individual 3D objects or "models".
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] These can be imported into a larger scene, or loaded on-demand by rendering software or games.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A realistic scene may require hundreds of items like household objects, vehicles, and trees, and 3D artists often utilize large libraries of models.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In game production, these models (along with other data such as textures, audio files, and animations) are referred to as "assets".
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Scientific and engineering visualization often requires rendering volumetric data generated by 3D scans or simulations.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Perhaps the most common source of such data is medical CT and MRI scans, which need to be rendered for diagnosis.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Volumetric data can be extremely large, and requires specialized data formats to store it efficiently, particularly if the volume is *sparse* (with empty regions that do not contain data).
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Before rendering, level sets for volumetric data can be extracted and converted into a mesh of triangles, e.g. by using the marching cubes algorithm.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Algorithms have also been developed that work directly with volumetric data, for example to render realistic depictions of the way light is scattered and absorbed by clouds and smoke, and this type of volumetric rendering is used extensively in visual effects for movies.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] When rendering lower-resolution volumetric data without interpolation, the individual cubes or "voxels" may be visible, an effect sometimes used deliberately for game graphics.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Photographs of real world objects can be incorporated into a rendered scene by using them as textures for 3D objects.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Photos of a scene can also be stitched together to create panoramic images or environment maps, which allow the scene to be rendered very efficiently but only from a single viewpoint.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Scanning of real objects and scenes using structured light or lidar produces point clouds consisting of the coordinates of millions of individual points in space, sometimes along with color information.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] These point clouds may either be rendered directly or converted into meshes before rendering.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A more recent, experimental approach is description of scenes using radiance fields which define the color, intensity, and direction of incoming light at each point in space.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] (This is conceptually similar to, but not identical to, the light field recorded by a hologram.) For any useful resolution, the amount of data in a radiance field is so large that it is impractical to represent it directly as volumetric data, and an approximation function must be found.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Neural networks are typically used to generate and evaluate these approximations, sometimes using video frames, or a collection of photographs of a scene taken at different angles, as "training data".
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Algorithms related to neural networks have recently been used to find approximations of a scene as 3D Gaussians.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The resulting representation is similar to a point cloud, except that it uses fuzzy, partially-transparent blobs of varying dimensions and orientations instead of points.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] As with neural radiance fields, these approximations are often generated from photographs or video frames.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The output of rendering may be displayed immediately on the screen (many times a second, in the case of real-time rendering such as games) or saved in a raster graphics file format such as JPEG or PNG.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] High-end rendering applications commonly use the OpenEXR file format, which can represent finer gradations of colors and high dynamic range lighting, allowing tone mapping or other adjustments to be applied afterwards without loss of quality.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The output of a renderer sometimes includes more than just RGB color values.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Transparency information can be included, allowing rendered foreground objects to be composited with photographs or video.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] It is also sometimes useful to store the contributions of different lights, or of specular and diffuse lighting, as separate channels, so lighting can be adjusted after rendering.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The OpenEXR format allows storing many channels of data in a single file.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Renderers such as Blender and Pixar RenderMan support a large variety of configurable values called Arbitrary Output Variables (AOVs).
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Choosing how to render a 3D scene usually involves trade-offs between speed, memory usage, and realism (although realism is not always desired).
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The **algorithms** developed over the years follow a loose progression, with more advanced methods becoming practical as computing power and memory capacity increased.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Multiple techniques may be used for a single final image.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] An important distinction is between image order algorithms, which iterate over pixels in the image, and object order algorithms, which iterate over objects in the scene.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For simple scenes, object order is usually more efficient, as there are fewer objects than pixels.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] algorithms that also support filled shapes.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In principle, any 2D vector graphics renderer can be used to render 3D objects by first projecting them onto a 2D image plane.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Different realistic or stylized effects can be obtained by coloring the pixels covered by the objects in different ways.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rasterization is usually synonymous with "object order" rendering (as described above).
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It can be used to implement "image order" rendering by casting a ray for each pixel, and finding a corresponding point in the scene.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] , requiring a varying number of ray casting operations for each path.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] is usually in the domain of path tracing.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] approach that breaks surfaces in the scene into pieces, and estimates the amount of light that each piece receives from light sources, or indirectly from other surfaces.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] of each surface is known, the scene can be rendered using rasterization or ray tracing.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] , giving ray tracing a rigorous mathematical foundation.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Each of the above approaches has many variations, and there is some overlap.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Path tracing may be considered either a distinct technique or a particular type of ray tracing.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Note that the usage of terminology related to ray tracing and path tracing has changed significantly over time.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray marching is a family of algorithms, used by ray casting, for finding intersections between a ray and a complex object, such as a volumetric dataset or a surface defined by a signed distance function.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It is not, by itself, a rendering method, but it can be incorporated into ray tracing and path tracing, and is used by rasterization to implement screen-space reflection and other effects.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A technique called photon mapping traces paths of photons from a light source to an object, accumulating data about irradiance which is then used during conventional ray tracing or path tracing.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rendering a scene using only rays traced from the light source to the camera is impractical, even though it corresponds more closely to reality, because a huge number of photons would need to be simulated, only a tiny fraction of which actually hit the camera.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Some authors call conventional ray tracing "backward" ray tracing because it traces the paths of photons backwards from the camera to the light source, and call following paths from the light source (as in photon mapping) "forward" ray tracing.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] However, sometimes the meaning of these terms is reversed.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Tracing rays starting at the light source can also be called *particle tracing* or *light tracing*, which avoids this ambiguity.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Real-time rendering, including video game graphics, typically uses rasterization, but increasingly combines it with ray tracing and path tracing.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] To enable realistic global illumination, real-time rendering often relies on pre-rendered ("baked") lighting for stationary objects.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For moving objects, it may use a technique called *light probes*, in which lighting is recorded by rendering omnidirectional views of the scene at chosen points in space (often points on a grid to allow easier interpolation).
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] These are similar to environment maps, but typically use a very low resolution or an approximation such as spherical harmonics.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The term *rasterization* (in a broad sense) encompasses many techniques used for 2D rendering and real-time 3D rendering.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] 3D animated films were rendered by rasterization before ray tracing and path tracing became practical.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A renderer combines rasterization with *geometry processing* (which is not specific to rasterization) and *pixel processing* which computes the RGB color values to be placed in the *framebuffer* for display.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Historically, 3D rasterization used algorithms like the *Warnock algorithm* and *scanline rendering* (also called "scan-conversion"), which can handle arbitrary polygons and can rasterize many shapes simultaneously.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Although such algorithms are still important for 2D rendering, 3D rendering now usually divides shapes into triangles and rasterizes them individually using simpler methods.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] High-performance algorithms exist for rasterizing 2D lines, including anti-aliased lines, as well as ellipses and filled triangles.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] An important special case of 2D rasterization is text rendering, which requires careful anti-aliasing and rounding of coordinates to avoid distorting the letterforms and preserve spacing, density, and sharpness.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] After 3D coordinates have been projected onto the image plane, rasterization is primarily a 2D problem, but the 3rd dimension necessitates *hidden surface removal*.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Early computer graphics used geometric algorithms or ray casting to remove the hidden portions of shapes, or used the *painter's algorithm*, which sorts shapes by depth (distance from camera) and renders them from back to front.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Depth sorting was later avoided by incorporating depth comparison into the scanline rendering algorithm.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The *z-buffer* algorithm performs the comparisons indirectly by including a depth or "z" value in the framebuffer.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A pixel is only covered by a shape if that shape's z value is lower (indicating closer to the camera) than the z value currently in the buffer.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The z-buffer requires additional memory (an expensive resource at the time it was invented) but simplifies the rasterization code and permits multiple passes.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Memory is now faster and more plentiful, and a z-buffer is almost always used for real-time rendering.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A drawback of the basic z-buffer algorithm is that each pixel ends up either entirely covered by a single object or filled with the background color, causing jagged edges in the final image.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Early *anti-aliasing* approaches addressed this by detecting when a pixel is partially covered by a shape, and calculating the covered area.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The A-buffer (and other supersampling and multi-sampling techniques) solve the problem less precisely but with higher performance.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For real-time 3D graphics, it has become common to use complicated heuristics (and even neural-networks) to perform anti-aliasing.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In 3D rasterization, color is usually determined by a *pixel shader* or *fragment shader*, a small program that is run for each pixel.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Until relatively recently, Pixar used rasterization for rendering its animated films.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Unlike the renderers commonly used for real-time graphics, the Reyes rendering system in Pixar's RenderMan software was optimized for rendering very small (pixel-sized) polygons, and incorporated stochastic sampling techniques more typically associated with ray tracing.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] One of the simplest ways to render a 3D scene is to test if a ray starting at the viewpoint (the "eye" or "camera") intersects any of the geometric shapes in the scene, repeating this test using a different ray direction for each pixel.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This method, called *ray casting*, was important in early computer graphics, and is a fundamental building block for more advanced algorithms.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray casting can be used to render shapes defined by *constructive solid geometry* (CSG) operations.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Early ray casting experiments include the work of Arthur Appel in the 1960s.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Appel rendered shadows by casting an additional ray from each visible surface point towards a light source.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] He also tried rendering the density of illumination by casting random rays from the light source towards the object and plotting the intersection points (similar to the later technique called *photon mapping*).
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] When rendering scenes containing many objects, testing the intersection of a ray with every object becomes very expensive.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Special data structures are used to speed up this process by allowing large numbers of objects to be excluded quickly (such as objects behind the camera).
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] These structures are analogous to database indexes for finding the relevant objects.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The most common are the *bounding volume hierarchy* (BVH), which stores a pre-computed bounding box or sphere for each branch of a tree of objects, and the *k-d tree* which recursively divides space into two parts.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Recent GPUs include hardware acceleration for BVH intersection tests.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] K-d trees are a special case of *binary space partitioning*, which was frequently used in early computer graphics (it can also generate a rasterization order for the painter's algorithm).
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] *Octrees*, another historically popular technique, are still often used for volumetric data.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Geometric formulas are sufficient for finding the intersection of a ray with shapes like spheres, polygons, and polyhedra, but for most curved surfaces there is no analytic solution, or the intersection is difficult to compute accurately using limited precision floating point numbers.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Root-finding algorithms such as Newton's method can sometimes be used.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] To avoid these complications, curved surfaces are often approximated as meshes of triangles.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Volume rendering (e.g. rendering clouds and smoke), and some surfaces such as fractals, may require ray marching instead of basic ray casting.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray casting can be used to render an image by tracing light rays backwards from a simulated camera.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] After finding a point on a surface where a ray originated, another ray is traced towards the light source to determine if anything is casting a shadow on that point.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] If there are multiple light sources, brightness contributions of the lights are added together.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For color images, calculations are repeated for multiple wavelengths of light (e.g. red, green, and blue).
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray tracing usually performs anti-aliasing by taking the average of multiple samples for each pixel.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It may also use multiple samples for effects like depth of field and motion blur.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] If evenly spaced ray directions or times are used for each of these features, many rays are required, and some aliasing will remain.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] *Cook-style*, *stochastic*, or *Monte Carlo ray tracing* avoids this problem by using random sampling instead of evenly spaced samples.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This type of ray tracing is commonly called *distributed ray tracing*, or *distribution ray tracing* because it samples rays from probability distributions.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Distribution ray tracing can also render realistic "soft" shadows from large lights by using a random sample of points on the light when testing for shadowing, and it can simulate chromatic aberration by sampling multiple wavelengths from the spectrum of light.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Real surface materials reflect small amounts of light in almost every direction because they have small (or microscopic) bumps and grooves.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A distribution ray tracer can simulate this by sampling possible ray directions, which allows rendering blurry reflections from glossy and metallic surfaces.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] However, if this procedure is repeated recursively to simulate realistic indirect lighting, and if more than one sample is taken at each surface point, the tree of rays quickly becomes huge.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Another kind of ray tracing, called *path tracing*, handles indirect light more efficiently, avoiding branching, and ensures that the distribution of all possible paths from a light source to the camera is sampled in an unbiased way.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray tracing was often used for rendering reflections in animated films, until path tracing became standard for film rendering.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Films such as Shrek 2 and Monsters University also used distribution ray tracing or path tracing to precompute indirect illumination for a scene or frame prior to rendering it using rasterization.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Advances in GPU technology have made real-time ray tracing possible in games, although it is currently almost always used in combination with rasterization.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This enables visual effects that are difficult with only rasterization, including reflection from curved surfaces and interreflective objects, and shadows that are accurate over a wide range of distances and surface orientations.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray tracing support is included in recent versions of the graphics APIs used by games, such as DirectX, Metal, and Vulkan.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray tracing has been used to render simulated black holes, and the appearance of objects moving at close to the speed of light, by taking spacetime curvature and relativistic effects into account during light ray simulation.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Radiosity (named after the radiometric quantity of the same name) is a method for rendering objects illuminated by light bouncing off rough or matte surfaces.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This type of illumination is called *indirect light*, *environment lighting*, *diffuse lighting*, or *diffuse interreflection*, and the problem of rendering it realistically is called *global illumination*.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rasterization and basic forms of ray tracing (other than distribution ray tracing and path tracing) can only roughly approximate indirect light, e.g. by adding a uniform "ambient" lighting amount chosen by the artist.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Radiosity techniques are also suited to rendering scenes with *area lights* such as rectangular fluorescent lighting panels, which are difficult for rasterization and traditional ray tracing.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In the original radiosity method (first proposed in 1984) now called *classical radiosity*, surfaces and lights in the scene are split into pieces called *patches*, a process called *meshing* (this step makes it a finite element method).
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The rendering code must then determine what fraction of the light being emitted or diffusely reflected (scattered) by each patch is received by each other patch.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] These fractions are called *form factors* or *view factors* (first used in engineering to model radiative heat transfer).
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The form factors are multiplied by the albedo of the receiving surface and put in a matrix.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The lighting in the scene can then be expressed as a matrix equation (or equivalently a system of linear equations) that can be solved by methods from linear algebra.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Solving the radiosity equation gives the total amount of light emitted and reflected by each patch, which is divided by area to get a value called *radiosity* that can be used when rasterizing or ray tracing to determine the color of pixels corresponding to visible parts of the patch.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For real-time rendering, this value (or more commonly the irradiance, which does not depend on local surface albedo) can be pre-computed and stored in a texture (called an *irradiance map*) or stored as vertex data for 3D models.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This feature was used in architectural visualization software to allow real-time walk-throughs of a building interior after computing the lighting.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The large size of the matrices used in classical radiosity (the square of the number of patches) causes problems for realistic scenes.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Practical implementations may use Jacobi or Gauss-Seidel iterations, which is equivalent (at least in the Jacobi case) to simulating the propagation of light one bounce at a time until the amount of light remaining (not yet absorbed by surfaces) is insignificant.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Form factors may be recomputed when they are needed, to avoid storing a complete matrix in memory.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The quality of rendering is often determined by the size of the patches, e.g. very fine meshes are needed to depict the edges of shadows accurately.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] An important improvement is *hierarchical radiosity*, which uses a coarser mesh (larger patches) for simulating the transfer of light between surfaces that are far away from one another, and adaptively sub-divides the patches as needed.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This allows radiosity to be used for much larger and more complex scenes.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Alternative and extended versions of the radiosity method support non-Lambertian surfaces, such as glossy surfaces and mirrors, and sometimes use volumes or "clusters" of objects as well as surface patches.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Simplified and partially precomputed versions of radiosity are widely used for real-time rendering, combined with techniques such as *octree radiosity* that store approximations of the light field.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] As part of the approach known as *physically based rendering*, **path tracing** has become the dominant technique for rendering realistic scenes, including effects for movies.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For example, the popular open source 3D software Blender uses path tracing in its Cycles renderer.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Like *distributed ray tracing*, path tracing is a kind of *stochastic* or *randomized* ray tracing that uses Monte Carlo or Quasi-Monte Carlo integration.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It was proposed and named in 1986 by Jim Kajiya in the same paper as the rendering equation.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Kajiya suggested reducing the noise present in the output images by using *stratified sampling* and *importance sampling* for making random decisions such as choosing which ray to follow at each step of a path.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Even with these techniques, path tracing would not have been practical for film rendering, using computers available at the time, because the computational cost of generating enough samples to reduce variance to an acceptable level was too high.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Monster House, the first feature film rendered entirely using path tracing, was not released until 20 years later.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In its basic form, path tracing is inefficient (requiring too many samples) for rendering caustics and scenes where light enters indirectly through narrow spaces.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Attempts were made to address these weaknesses in the 1990s.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] *Metropolis light transport* samples paths by modifying paths that were previously traced, spending more time exploring paths that are similar to other "bright" paths, which increases the chance of discovering even brighter paths.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] *Multiple importance sampling* provides a way to reduce variance when combining samples from more than one sampling method, particularly when some samples are much noisier than the others.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This later work was summarized and expanded upon in Eric Veach's 1997 PhD thesis, which helped raise interest in path tracing in the computer graphics community.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The Arnold renderer, first released in 1998, proved that path tracing was practical for rendering frames for films, and that there was a demand for unbiased and physically based rendering in the film industry; other commercial and open source path tracing renderers began appearing.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Computational cost was addressed by rapid advances in CPU and cluster performance.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Path tracing's relative simplicity and its nature as a Monte Carlo method (sampling hundreds or thousands of paths per pixel) have made it attractive to implement on a GPU, especially on recent GPUs that support ray tracing acceleration technology such as Nvidia's RTX and OptiX.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] However bidirectional path tracing and Metropolis light transport are more difficult to implement efficiently on a GPU.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Techniques have been developed to denoise the output of path tracing, reducing the number of paths required to achieve acceptable quality, at the risk of losing some detail or introducing small-scale artifacts that are more objectionable than noise.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Neural networks are now widely used for this purpose.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Research into improving path tracing continues.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Many variations of bidirectional path tracing and Metropolis light transport have been explored, and ways of combining path tracing with photon mapping.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Recent *path guiding* approaches construct approximations of the light field probability distribution in each volume of space, so paths can be sampled more effectively.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] By combining denoising and hardware ray tracing acceleration, it is now practical to use path tracing for real-time rendering.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Due to performance constraints, biased techniques such as a radiance cache may be incorporated.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Spatiotemporal reservoir resampling (ReSTIR) aims to improve the quality of real-time path tracing and allow more complex lighting by reusing samples (paths) from previous frames and adjacent pixels.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] As of 2003, machine learning (ML) techniques were being used in other areas of computer graphics, such as texture synthesis, fitting surfaces to point clouds, and fitting curves to motion capture data.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The use of ML for rendering expanded with the availability of GPUs that can evaluate neural networks (especially convolutional neural networks) quickly.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Neural networks and Gaussian mixture models have been used in conjunction with rendering techniques such as path tracing to encode bidirectional reflectance distribution functions (BRDFs), or to encode cached radiance at points in space (for biased acceleration of rendering or for path guiding).
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Neural radiance fields (NeRFs) take the latter approach to an extreme, encoding radiance at all points in a volume, and using evaluation of this approximation as the primary rendering method.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] One of the most widely used applications of machine learning in rendering is denoising of path traced images (in practice, most path tracing now likely uses such a denoiser).
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Denoisers specialized for real-time rendering can work with very low sample counts and improve temporal coherence to reduce flickering.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rendering is usually limited by available computing power and memory bandwidth, and so specialized hardware has been developed to speed it up ("accelerate" it), particularly for real-time rendering.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Hardware features such as a framebuffer for raster graphics are required to display the output of rendering smoothly in real time.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Hardware acceleration does not replace the use of software for rendering, rather it speeds up selected operations or calculations using dedicated circuits, or runs portions of the software's code on a different type of processor.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In the era of vector monitors (also called *calligraphic displays*), a display processing unit (DPU) was a dedicated CPU or coprocessor that maintained a list of visual elements and redrew them continuously on the screen by controlling an electron beam.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Advanced DPUs such as Evans & Sutherland's Line Drawing System-1 (and later models produced into the 1980s) incorporated 3D coordinate transformation features to accelerate rendering of wire-frame images.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Evans & Sutherland also made the Digistar planetarium projection system, which was a vector display that could render both stars and wire-frame graphics (the vector-based Digistar and Digistar II were used in many planetariums, and a few may still be in operation).
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A Digistar prototype was used for rendering 3D star fields for the film Star Trek II: The Wrath of Khan – some of the first 3D computer graphics sequences ever seen in a feature film.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Shaded 3D graphics rendering in the 1970s and early 1980s was usually implemented on general-purpose computers, such as the PDP-10 used by researchers at the University of Utah.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It was difficult to speed up using specialized hardware because it involves a pipeline of complex steps, requiring data addressing, decision-making, and computation capabilities typically only provided by CPUs (although dedicated circuits for speeding up particular operations were proposed ).
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Supercomputers or specially designed multi-CPU computers or clusters were sometimes used for ray tracing.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Clark and Marc Hannah designed the Geometry Engine, a VLSI chip for performing some of the steps of the 3D rasterization pipeline, and started the company Silicon Graphics (SGI) to commercialize this technology.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Home computers and game consoles in the 1980s contained graphics coprocessors that were capable of scrolling and filling areas of the display, and drawing sprites and lines, though they were not useful for rendering realistic images.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Towards the end of the 1980s PC graphics cards and arcade games with 3D rendering acceleration began to appear, and in the 1990s such technology became commonplace.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Today, even low-power mobile processors typically incorporate 3D graphics acceleration features.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The 3D graphics accelerators of the 1990s evolved into modern GPUs.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] GPUs are general-purpose processors, like CPUs, but they are designed for tasks that can be broken into many small, similar, mostly independent sub-tasks (such as rendering individual pixels) and performed in parallel.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Due to their origins, GPUs typically still provide specialized hardware acceleration for some steps of a traditional 3D rasterization pipeline, including hidden surface removal using a z-buffer, and texture mapping with mipmaps, but these features are no longer always used.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Recent GPUs have features to accelerate finding the intersections of rays with a bounding volume hierarchy, to help speed up all variants of ray tracing and path tracing, as well as neural network acceleration features sometimes useful for rendering.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rendering algorithms will run efficiently on a GPU only if they can be implemented using small groups of threads that perform mostly the same operations.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] As an example of code that meets this requirement: when rendering a small square of pixels in a simple ray-traced image, all threads will likely be intersecting rays with the same object and performing the same lighting computations.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For performance and architectural reasons, GPUs run groups of around 16-64 threads called *warps* or *wavefronts* in lock-step (all threads in the group are executing the same instructions at the same time).
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] If not all threads in the group need to run particular blocks of code (due to conditions) then some threads will be idle, or the results of their computations will be discarded, causing degraded performance.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Historically, the term *hardware rendering* (possibly an abbreviation of "hardware accelerated rendering" or "hardware-assisted rendering") was sometimes used to mean rendering using a hardware-accelerated rasterization pipeline (typically for real-time rendering).
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In contrast, *software rendering* meant offline rendering using software that was not limited by the capabilities of graphics hardware, and could use more realistic and higher quality techniques.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Both hardware and software have evolved, and although these terms are still used, their meaning may now be context-dependent.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] When OpenGL and Direct3D were introduced in the 1990s, there was a need to use these APIs on computers that did not have hardware acceleration for 3D graphics.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] "Fallback" rendering implementations were provided that did not require special hardware, and these are sometimes called "software renderers" (today hardware acceleration is almost always available, and these CPU-only implementations are used primarily for testing).
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] More recently, "software rendering" may also mean rendering that does not use graphics APIs such as OpenGL, Metal, Direct3D, or Vulkan.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Types of renderers that in the past might have been called "software renderers" (e.g. path tracing renderers used for offline rendering for movies) now commonly use GPU acceleration, often via APIs such as CUDA or OpenCL, which are not graphics-specific.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Since these latter APIs allow running C++ code on a GPU, it is now possible to run the same rendering code on either a CPU or GPU.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The following is a rough timeline of frequently mentioned rendering techniques, including areas of current research.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Note that even in cases where an idea was named in a specific paper, there were almost always multiple researchers or teams working in the same area (including earlier related work).
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] When a method is first proposed it is often very inefficient, and it takes additional research and practical efforts to turn it into a useful technique.
[src:dearpygui/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The list focuses on academic research and does not include hardware.
[src:dearpygui/retained-mode] Immediate mode is an alternative approach.
[src:dearpygui/retained-mode] Historically, retained mode has been the dominant style in GUI libraries; however, both can coexist in the same library and are not necessarily exclusionary in practice.
[src:dearpygui/retained-mode] In retained mode the client calls do not directly cause actual rendering, but instead update an abstract internal model (typically a list of objects) which is maintained within the library's data space.
[src:dearpygui/retained-mode] This allows the library to optimize when actual rendering takes place along with the processing of related objects.
[src:dearpygui/retained-mode] Example of coexistence with immediate mode in the same library is OpenGL.
[src:dearpygui/retained-mode] OpenGL has immediate mode functions that can use previously defined server side objects (textures, vertex buffers and index buffers, shaders, etc.) without resending unchanged data.
[src:dearpygui/retained-mode] Examples of retained mode rendering systems include Windows Presentation Foundation, SceneKit on macOS, and PHIGS.
